    <div class="elementListBrownSeparator"></div>



  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3256398296" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3256398296" />
    <a title="Brian Bess" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1035284-brian-bess"><img alt="Brian Bess" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1277585693p2/1035284.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3256398296?book_show_action=true">Mar 31, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brian Bess" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brian Bess" href="/user/show/1035284-brian-bess">Brian Bess</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3256398296" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13520287399425859942">Post-traumatic Cold War Disorder<br/><br/>The first fact about E.L. Doctorow’s 1971 novel ‘The Book of Daniel’ that everyone learns is that it is based on the case of Julius and Ethel Rosenberg, the first people in U.S. history to be executed for espionage. In Doctorow’s novel, the Rosenbergs are renamed Paul and Rochelle Isaacson and, rather than the two sons of the Rosenbergs, the Isaacsons have a son, Daniel, and a daughter, Susan. Daniel and Susan were children in the early 1950’s when their parents w</span>
  <span id="freeText13520287399425859942" style="display:none">Post-traumatic Cold War Disorder<br /><br />The first fact about E.L. Doctorow’s 1971 novel ‘The Book of Daniel’ that everyone learns is that it is based on the case of Julius and Ethel Rosenberg, the first people in U.S. history to be executed for espionage. In Doctorow’s novel, the Rosenbergs are renamed Paul and Rochelle Isaacson and, rather than the two sons of the Rosenbergs, the Isaacsons have a son, Daniel, and a daughter, Susan. Daniel and Susan were children in the early 1950’s when their parents were sent to the electric chair and so that event has largely defined and influenced the course of the rest of their lives.<br /><br />The novel is primarily concerned with the recollections of Daniel, who in the late 60’s has a wife, Phyllis, and a baby son, Paul, and is working on a dissertation for his PhD. on the history of the American Left, the large umbrella under which all subversive movements, including the ones that engulfed his parents, are clustered. It is impossible for Daniel to be objective about this topic considering his past and who he is, so the project becomes consumed with his personal psychotherapy, an exorcism of demons from his past, and an investigation of what really happened to his parents, what they did and how they were caught, implicated, and executed for their crimes. <br /><br />Throughout the novel, Daniel refers to himself as a “criminal of perception”. This mindset permeates through the prose, where it changes from third person to first and back within the same paragraph and moves to recollections of life in the Bronx where his father ran a radio repair shop. Daniel vividly recalls several dramatic incidents as experienced through the child’s point of view.<br /><br />Paul and Rochelle are very interested in joining a caravan of leftists to see great singer and socialist, Paul Robeson, perform. Rochelle is wary of bringing Daniel as she anticipates possible harassment but Paul talks her into consenting. After the concert, with everyone feeling freshly invigorated, the buses begin to take a different route and are beset by Fascist hoodlums breaking the windows with bats and throwing rocks through them. Paul’s indignation prompts him to move toward the front of the bus, trying to get the driver to move it but they are hemmed in by other buses in front as well as behind them. He tries to get the attention of a police officer, pushing open the bus door. His arm gets wedged between the doors, enabling the thugs to break it. Finally, the door swings open and Paul and a few others fall out on the ground where Paul is beaten. Daniel realizes that of all the terrorized people on the bus, Paul was the only one to try to take action.<br /><br />After Mindish is arrested, a couple of FBI men knock on the door. Paul is polite but states that he will be happy to answer any questions they may have in a court of law. He is not required to answer any questions they ask in his home. Paul and Rochelle know that they, or others like them, will return. When they finally do, to arrest Paul, it resembles Nazi stormtroopers ransacking Jewish homes before World War II. For a while, Rochelle tries to maintain a state of normalcy, keeping the radio store open long enough for customers to retrieve their radios, knowing that the Isaacson name is now a pariah. Then, Rochelle is arrested and the children are lost, staying with their aunt briefly, then a neighbor, then a Children’s Shelter, which Daniel and Susan both consider a jail. After a short while, Daniel finds his sister and they walk out of it and make their way back to their now boarded up home. The Isaacsons attorney, Jacob Ascher, tries to place them with a family that will be willing to adopt them. The junior partner, Robert Lewin, and his wife, Lise, agree and try to give them a loving home, made permanent by the executions of their parents.<br /><br />Flash forward to 1967 where Daniel is an angry, young graduate student with a wife and child and Susan is in a mental hospital after slitting her wrists. When she reached the age of claiming the trust fund her parents left her, Susan had wanted to start a foundation, to help educate students, to keep the revolution going. Daniel is ambivalent about it, yet he later attends an anti-draft rally at the Pentagon and gets beaten with the other protesters, getting his teeth broken. He later tells Phyllis, “It looks worse than it is. There was nothing to it. It’s a lot easier to be a revolutionary nowadays than it used to be.”<br /><br />When Paul thinks that the doctors are considering administering electric shock treatment on Susan, he is enraged and tries to hunt down the doctor and kill him. Considering the method of his parents’ execution it seems understandable that he would resist any thought of electrocuting another family member. He moves back to first person:<br />“I was learning how to be an Isaacson. An Isaacson does things boldly calculated to bring self-destructive results. It is a way of making the world do your bidding.”<br /><br />His investigation leads him to question Ascher’s bitter widow, who blames his parents for her husband’s early death. She says that his adopted father, Robert Lewin, has the files that may contain more information about the case. So Paul asks his father, who says the FBI operates from a list of well-known activists and from the list they seek vulnerable targets, which they found with Mindish. Their tactics were to try to get someone to implicate someone else, to name names in exchange for, if not immunity, then a lesser sentence. That was their original intent in arresting Rochelle. They thought she would crack under the pressure but she called their bluff and stood by her man, leaving her children orphaned. <br /><br />Throughout the novel, the Isaacsons are never seen doing any actual spying or stealing secrets to give to the Soviets. What we see is leftists giving voice to their Communist enthusiasms, exercising their right of free speech. Daniel twists himself in knots searching for a definitive truth that explains this wreckage to his life. He is bitter and angry and cruel to the people he loves. <br /><br />Doctorow weaves together a powerful tale of terror, trauma, and betrayal. However, he undercuts the power with linguistic tricks and diversions. All of the Isaacson children’s grievances are sexualized and summarized with the F word. Daniel inflicts sexual cruelty on his wife. And here is where Doctorow’s usually brilliant and engaging writing descends into awkwardness. I suppose one could defend him by saying that the sexualization and the awkwardness reflects Daniel’s fragmented and erratic viewpoint. The prose becomes disjointed with diversions, such as the extended discourse on the subliminal purposes of Disneyland, which seem superfluous. Other diversions are more to the point such as the discussions of methods of execution throughout history that culminate with the expected, excruciating depictions of the executions of each of Daniel’s parents. <br /><br />I can understand why Doctorow was emotionally devastated after writing this novel and unable to write anything else for a few years. It is harrowing to read and it must have been emotionally wrenching to live through these experiences with his characters. One does not have to be familiar with the Rosenberg case in order to appreciate ‘The Book of Daniel’. Doctorow was wise not to limit himself to the historic facts of their lives. Many may be disappointed that there is never any clear statement of the Isaacsons’ crimes and guilt. Since Doctorow was not going to take a definite stand on that matter, it probably served his purpose not to dramatize any of their actions that could be considered treasonous. We are left unsure and without certainty and, like Daniel, left to ponder and contemplate how all this could have happened.<br /><br /> <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="13520287399425859942" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

